# ✅ Shell Script: `mstrbak_auto.sh`

```bash
#!/bin/bash

# ===== Variables =====
MSTR_HOME="/opt/"
PROJECT_NAME="MSTRJan"

MSTR_USER="Administrator"
MSTR_PASS="CHANGE_ME"

DSN="MD Feb3"
DB_USER="MSTR11512MD"
DB_PASS="CHANGE_ME"

RESPONSE_FILE="/opt/mstrbkc/mstrbak/response.json"
BACKUP_PATH="/opt/mstrbkc/mstrbak"

MSTRBAK_BIN="/opt/mstrbkc/Mstrbak-client/mstrbak"

# ===== Run Backup =====
$MSTRBAK_BIN <<EOF

$MSTR_HOME
$PROJECT_NAME
$MSTR_USER
$MSTR_PASS
$DSN
$DB_USER
$DB_PASS

yes
no
no

no
no
no
no
no
no
no
no
no
no
no
no
no
$RESPONSE_FILE
$BACKUP_PATH
EOF
```

---

# ▶️ How to run

```bash
chmod +x mstrbak_auto.sh
./mstrbak_auto.sh
```

---

# 🔍 How this works

This line:

```bash
<<EOF
```

👉 Sends all inputs **exactly like you typed manually** 

Each line = one **Enter press**

---

# ⚠️ Important Notes

## ❗ 1. Order must match prompts EXACTLY

If MicroStrategy changes prompt order → script breaks

---

## ❗ 2. Blank lines matter

Example:

```bash
$DB_PASS

yes
```

👉 That blank line = **Metadata prefix (you pressed Enter)**

---

## ❗ 3. Password security (important)

Instead of hardcoding:

```bash
MSTR_PASS="CHANGE_ME"
```

Use:

```bash
read -s -p "Enter MSTR Password: " MSTR_PASS
echo
```

---

# 🔐 Secure Version (Recommended)

Replace password section:

```bash
read -s -p "Enter MSTR Password: " MSTR_PASS
echo
read -s -p "Enter DB Password: " DB_PASS
echo
```

